<br>
Silverblade, I have looked and looked for three days for some kind of evidence...ANY kind of evidence to support what you say about out of control extremism.  I mean, I've read articles and reports by agencies and think-tanks ranging from the CIA to the Washington Institute, CNN, Reuters, British JIC, Jane's, the Washington Quarterly...hell even NPR and the BBC.  I can't even remember them all.  It has been extremely educational, and was time well spent.  But guess what...I have found exactly <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>nothing</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that backs your claims.  Consensus?  A post-Saddam Iraq will be precarious and tricky, but not unmanageable.<br>
<br>
Well f**king duh.<br>
<br>
The current thinking is that after Saddam Hussein is removed, a US-lead coalition will  occupy and manage Iraq - not totally unlike what General MacArthur did in Japan after WWII.  Unlike in Japan, however, any temporary governance will have to be headed Iraqi civilians and backed by Western forces.  The Iraqi people would most likely not submit to having a Westerner calling the shots.  Which is fine, and completely understandable.  <br>
<br>
This occupation force will remain in place long enough to help rebuild infrastructure and build a functioning Iraqi government.  My guess is that it will be there long after that to babysit, much like we are in Bosnia/Kosovo.<br>
<br>
A few examples of this force's mandate(s) will be:<br>
To train and possibly help equip the Iraqi regular army (the RG and SRG will, by necessity, be decimated during any military action), which will play a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>major</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> role in the stabilization of a post-Saddam Iraq; to help rebuild infrastructure; to help the Iraqi army maintain security and stability; <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>to protect Iraq from any outside threat</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> (e.g. Iran)<br>
<br>
I do not doubt that there will be certain ultra-extremist groups that will have a problem with any Western presence in their country.  But, well...so what?  Believe it or not, we can deal with it /GASP.  Yeah, there will be people who do not want us there.  Surprise surprise.<br>
<br>
In any case, the idea that our presence will somehow cause Iraq and the region to go completely off the deep end over night is really without base.  Actually, the reason we will <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have problems with the Shi'ites is because <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>they are Saddam Hussein's BIGGIST OPPOSITION</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> for Christ's sake.  They want him gone more than we do.  Hell, I would not be surprised to see them fighting alongside us!  In fact, when speaking in terms of open, armed revolution, the Iraqi Shi'a have tried to overthrow Saddam Hussein as recently as 1991.  As did the Kurds in the north...and we know how that ended.<br>
<br>
Another misrepresentation of truth that you've put forth, which is further evidence of your overall lack of understanding, is that the Shi'a of southern Iraq will cause problems post-Saddam because Iraqi Shi'a = Iranian Shi'a.  This is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not the case</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  The two groups are not the same.  <br>
<br>
During the Iran-Iraq war, the Iranians thought they could depend on the Iraqi Shi'a to flock to them and do their bidding.  This did not happen.  Why didn't it happen?  Because the two groups - although Shi'ite Muslims - are not of the same ethnicity.  The Iraqi Shi'a do not have any allegience to the Iranians.  The Iraqi Shi'a identify themselves as Arabs...and more commonly, as Iraqis.  What the Iraqi Shi'a want is proportional representation in the central government.  They make up over 60% of the population, and the ruling Ba'ath party is almost exclusively Sunni.<br>
<br>
Anyway, that is why you are wrong.  I spent a few days of casual study in my spare time and gleaned a basic understanding that I didn't have before.  I would suggest that you follow my lead before you put forth asinine arguments about something you clearly do not understand.<br>
